    <h1>Calculating Measurement Uncertainty: The GUM Method</h1>
    <p><strong>Topic:</strong> Metrology & Quality | <strong>Standard:</strong> ISO/IEC Guide 98-3</p>
    <hr>

    <p>In metrology, a measurement is not complete without a statement of uncertainty. This guide summarizes the standard framework.</p>

    <h2>1. The Model Equation</h2>
    <p>The measurand \( Y \) is determined from \( N \) input quantities \( X_1, X_2, ..., X_N \) through a functional relationship:</p>
    $$ Y = f(X_1, X_2, ..., X_N) $$

    <h2>2. Law of Propagation of Uncertainty</h2>
    <p>The combined standard uncertainty \( u_c(y) \) is the positive square root of the combined variance:</p>
    
    $$ u_c^2(y) = \sum_{i=1}^{N} \left( \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_i} \right)^2 u^2(x_i) $$
    
    <div class="box">
        <strong>Key Concept:</strong> The term \( \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_i} \) is the sensitivity coefficient. It describes how much the output \( y \) changes when the input \( x_i \) changes.
    </div>

    <h2>3. Reporting the Result</h2>
    <p>The final result is reported as an Expanded Uncertainty \( U \), typically using a coverage factor \( k=2 \) (giving a level of confidence of approximately 95%).</p>
    $$ U = k \times u_c(y) $$

